 environment, where affairs of state were closely linked to the ruler's mental state, French writers sought new ways of representing the psychological dynamics of the body politic. This book explores the innovative mix of organic and inorganic metaphors through which they explored the relationship between mind, body and government at this period; in particular, it considers texts by such authors as Alan Chartier and Charles d'Orléans which describe mental illness and intellectual impairments through the notion of "rust". JULIE SINGER is Associate Professor of French at Washington University, St. Louis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFrench literaturexHistory and criticismyTo 1500. 0aLiterature and societyxHistoryyTo 1500zFrance. 0aMental illness in literature. 4aFrench Studies. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aBody.  aCharles VI.  aFifteenth Century.  aGovernment.  aLate Medieval France.  aMachines.  aMadness.  aMental Illness.  aMetaphor.  aMetaphorical Representations.  aMind.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311143106240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787443334?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787443334423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787443334/original  a978-3-11-143106-2  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles